const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What GE Monogram appliances do you repair in Los Angeles?",
    a: "All current Monogram US categories. Refrigerators (ZISS-series 42-inch and 48-inch built-in side-by-side, ZIC integrated columns 24-inch and 36-inch panel-ready, ZIR integrated all-refrigerator and all-freezer columns, ZWE counter-depth French Door variants), ranges (ZDP dual-fuel professional ranges 30 / 36 / 48-inch, ZGP gas, ZEP electric), wall ovens (ZET / ZSC single and double electric, Advantium ZSC speed-oven hybrid units), dishwashers (ZDT-series fully integrated panel-ready), cooktops (gas, induction, dual-fuel modular configurations), Advantium speed ovens (the signature halogen-plus-microwave hybrid technology), ventilation (downdraft and wall-mount hoods matching the range collections), and wine and beverage storage. Within Monogram's actual US lineup we service the full range; 2010-onward manufacture dates dominant in our service mix."
  },
  {
    q: "How much does GE Monogram refrigerator repair cost in LA?",
    a: "Diagnostic is $89, applied toward the repair when you approve the work. Common Monogram refrigerator repairs: ice maker fill valve $185-$285 (the most common ZISS-series service item, especially the 2015-2020 cohort in hard-water LA addresses); ice maker assembly $345-$525; evaporator fan motor $245-$385; condenser fan motor $285-$425; defrost system (heater + thermostat + sensor) $245-$385; main control board $445-$680; door gasket replacement $185-$285; ZIC column door hinge alignment $245-$385 (flush-mount integration requires specific shim adjustment); water inlet valve $185-$285; LED light panel $185-$285 (older units may use halogen modules — Monogram transitioned to LED across the 2017 production year). Compressor replacement on out-of-warranty units (year 10+) runs $580-$880 — and on a Monogram at that price point we always walk through repair-vs-replace math because the cabinet has another 8-10 years of life. Parts via GE Appliances' US network (Louisville Kentucky distribution backbone), typical 2-5 day lead time — significantly faster than European-supply luxury brands; common wear parts on the truck for the dominant ZISS / ZIC / ZDT series."
  },
  {
    q: "My GE Monogram built-in refrigerator isn't cooling — what's the likely cause?",
    a: "Three most common causes on Monogram ZISS-series and ZIC-column refrigerators in LA, in diagnostic order: (1) Condenser coil fouling. Monogram built-in units have condenser placement under the unit or behind the front kick plate where dust and pet hair accumulate faster than people expect — especially in LA homes with carpet adjacent to the kitchen or pets that shed near the unit. Sometimes a no-parts cleaning service restores cooling fully (~$120 labor only). (2) Evaporator fan motor failure. The fan in the freezer compartment circulates cold air to the fresh-food side; when it fails, freezer holds temp normally but fresh-food side warms up. Distinct symptom — freezer fine, fridge warm. $245-$385 replacement, typically same-day when we stock the common ZISS / ZIC evap fans on the truck. (3) Defrost system fault (heater, thermostat, or sensor). Frost builds on the evaporator coil and blocks airflow even though the fan still spins. Often presents as warming intermittently then recovering after a manual defrost cycle. $245-$385 typical. Less common but real on older units: main control board failure ($445-$680), refrigerant leak in the sealed system (compressor work territory, year 10+ math). We diagnose on-site and tell you the actual cause before any parts get ordered."
  },
  {
    q: "Is GE Monogram the same as GE Profile?",
    a: "Same parent manufacturer (GE Appliances, owned by Haier since 2016) but distinctly different tiers with different parts ecosystems. GE Appliances runs a three-tier premium hierarchy in the US: <strong>Monogram</strong> sits at the top — luxury built-in refrigerators, professional ranges, Advantium speed ovens, fully-integrated dishwashers, designed to compete with Sub-Zero / Wolf / Miele at a slightly lower price point. <strong>GE Café</strong> is the middle tier — design-forward style with customizable handles and finishes, mid-luxury positioning. <strong>GE Profile</strong> is the entry-premium tier — quality construction with smart features, positioned above the mass-market GE line. Practical service implication: a Monogram refrigerator and a Profile refrigerator look superficially similar but use different chassis platforms, different control boards, different parts numbering. Service shops that don't distinguish between Monogram, Profile, and Café often quote the wrong parts on a Monogram unit. Our techs identify the brand and tier from the model number on the inside-door tag before parts are ordered — that's the first step on every GE-family service call."
  },
  {
    q: "Does Haier ownership affect GE Monogram parts availability?",
    a: "No — and this is worth saying clearly because misinformation runs around the topic. Haier acquired GE Appliances from General Electric in 2016, but the practical impact on US service was minimal. The GE Appliances headquarters remains in Louisville, Kentucky; Monogram engineering and design continue in Louisville; the US parts network (warehouses across the country, distributor relationships, technician training programs) continues operating as before. Monogram parts ship through GE Appliances' established US channel with typical 2-5 day lead time — significantly faster than European luxury brands (Liebherr, Gaggenau, Asko, Miele) which run 5-14 day lead from overseas distribution. Six-plus years post-acquisition, parts availability for Monogram refrigerators, ranges, wall ovens, dishwashers, and Advantium speed ovens remains excellent. Customers worried about parts after the Haier transition can stop worrying — the GE Appliances service infrastructure is intact and well-resourced."
  },
  {
    q: "Can you repair GE Monogram Advantium speed ovens?",
    a: "Yes — and Advantium is genuinely different from standard wall ovens or microwaves, so it's worth knowing how the service tree differs. Advantium is GE's hybrid speed-cooking technology that combines halogen lamps (for the radiant browning) with microwave energy (for the through-cooking) in a single oven cavity. The unit cooks measurably faster than a standard convection oven and produces browning that a standard microwave can't. Service items on Advantium units: halogen lamps (year 3-6 typical service interval, $145-$265 per lamp depending on the specific model), magnetron tube (year 7-10, $345-$525 — same as standard microwave magnetrons), high-voltage capacitor and diode ($185-$285), door interlock switches ($165-$245), control board ($445-$680), turntable motor on units that have one. Diagnostic identifies whether the halogen side or the microwave side has failed — sometimes the unit appears completely dead but only one cooking mode has failed, and the diagnostic separates which. We service the ZSC / ZWB Advantium models and similar variants across the Monogram and Café tiers (Advantium technology spans both)."
  },
